          "explanation": "We denote each inhabitant\u2019s type as a Boolean: true = knight, false = knave.\n\n- Alice\u2019s statement: \u201cBob is a knave.\u201d  \n  Truth value = (Bob = false).  \n  If Alice is a knight (true) then Bob must be false; if Alice is a knave (false) then Bob must be true.  \n  Hence **Bob = \u00acAlice**.\n\n- Charlie\u2019s statement: \u201cAlice is a knave.\u201d  \n  Truth value = (Alice = false).  \n  If Charlie is a knight then Alice = false; if Charlie is a knave then Alice = true.  \n  Hence **Alice = \u00acCharlie**, i.e., **Charlie = \u00acAlice**.\n\nThus Bob and Charlie have the same type: both equal \u00acAlice.\n\n- Bob\u2019s statement: \u201cAlice and Charlie are of the same type.\u201d  \n  Truth value = (Alice = Charlie).  \n  Since Charlie = \u00acAlice, Alice = Charlie is equivalent to Alice = \u00acAlice, which is true only when Alice is false.  \n  Therefore, if Bob is a knight (true) we must have Alice = Charlie, which fails when Alice = true.  \n  The only consistent assignment is: Alice = true (knight), then Bob = false, Charlie = false, and Bob\u2019s statement is false (as required for a knave).\n\nChecking all statements:\n- Alice (knight) says \u201cBob is a knave.\u201d \u2013 true (Bob is knave).  \n- Bob (knave) says \u201cAlice and Charlie are the same type.\u201d \u2013 false (Alice is knight, Charlie is knave).  \n- Charlie (knave) says \u201cAlice is a knave.\u201d \u2013 false (Alice is knight).\n\nAll conditions are satisfied, and the alternative where Alice is knave leads to a contradiction. Hence the unique solution is:\nAlice \u2013 knight, Bob \u2013 knave, Charlie \u2013 knave."
